 and the worlds that fade and the ones that become visible in the process. He shares the stories of a disillusioned anarchist organizer, an exhausted nurse helping a father searching for his lost daughter, a misunderstood Romani man rejected by his friends and family, an undocumented migrant who discovers hope in the trash—stories of individuals finding solace and possibility within, with, and against the tragedies of their lives. Alexandrakis shows how these stories lead to a potentially transformative coming to resilience. In Radical Resilience, Alexandrakis traces the bare edges of radical possibility from within the efforts of those continuing on beyond their limits.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMarginality, SocialzGreecezAthens. 0aResilience (Personality trait)zGreecezAthens. 0aSufferingxSocial aspectszGreecezAthens. 4aAnthropology. 4aSociology & Social Science. 4aWest European History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Greece (see also Ancient / Greece).2bisacsh  asovereign debt crisis and austerity measures, resilience in Greece, resilience in athens, 2008 financial crisis, life of people in greece, austerity and precarity on Athenians,.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311075182640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150176146140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501761461423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501761461/original  a978-3-11-075182-6  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK